ve the required creep performance after heat-treatment.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 18 May 2021 06:47:17 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-05-19"}
{"id":"2105.08308","submitter":"Birenjith Sasidharan","authors":"K. S. Ajish Kumar, Birenjith Sasidharan, K. S. Sudeep","title":"On Oriented Diameter of $(n, k)$-Star Graphs","comments":"Revised version contains proof of a lemma that was omitted earlier.\n  It also elucidates a few arguments in the proof of main theorem. The section\n  on comparison with other works is rewritten for clarity","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cs.DM math.CO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Assignment of one of the two possible directions to every edge of an\nundirected graph $G=(V,E)$ is called an orientation of $G$. The resulting\ndirected graph is denoted by $\\overrightarrow{G}$. A strong orientation is one\nin which every vertex is reachable from every other vertex via a directed path.\nThe diameter of $\\overrightarrow{G}$, i.e., the maximum distance from one\nvertex to another, depends on the particular orientation. The minimum diameter\namong all possible orientations is called the oriented diameter\n$\\overrightarrow{\\text{diam}}(G)$ of $G$. Let $n,k$ be two integers with $1\n\\leq k < n$. In the realm of interconnection networks of processing elements,\nan $(n,k)$-star graph $S_{n,k}$ offers a topology that circumvents the lack of\nscalability of $n$-star graphs $S_n$. In this paper, we present a strong\norientation for $S_{n,k}$ that combines approaches suggested by Cheng and\nLipman [Journal of Interconnection Networks (2002)] for $S_{n,k}$ with the one\nproposed by Fujita [The First International Symposium on Computing and\nNetworking (CANDAR 2013)] for $S_n$. Next, we propose a distributed routing\nalgorithm for $\\overrightarrow{S_{n,k}}$ inspired by an algorithm proposed by\nKumar, Rajendraprasad and Sudeep [Discrete Applied Mathematics (2021)] for\n$\\overrightarrow{S_n}$. With the aid of both the orientation scheme and the\nrouting algorithm, we show that $\\overrightarrow{\\text{diam}}(S_{n,k}) \\leq\n\\lfloor \\frac{n+k}{2} \\rfloor + 2k + 6 - \\delta(n,k)$ where $\\delta(n,k)$ is a\nnon-negative function. The function $\\delta(n,k)$ takes on values $2k-n$, $0$,\nand $\\left\\lfloor \\frac{n-3k}{2} \\right\\rfloor$ respectively for three disjoint\nintervals $k>\\frac{n}{2}$, $\\frac{n}{3} < k \\leq \\frac{n}{2}$ and $k\\leq\n\\frac{n}{3}$. For every value of $n$, $k$, our upper bound performs better than\nall known bounds in literature.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 18 May 2021 06:51:08 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 28 Mar 2022 15:43:26 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-03-29"}
