{"id":"2105.08610","submitter":"Hans  Cuypers","authors":"Hans Cuypers","title":"Whitney's Theorem for Line Graphs of Multi-Graphs","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.CO","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0/","abstract":"  Whitney's Theorem states that every graph, different from $K_3$ or $K_{1,3}$,\nis uniquely determined by its line graph. A $1$-line graph of a multi-graph is\nthe graph with as vertices the edges of the multi-graph, and two edges adjacent\nif and only if there is a unique vertex on both edges. The $\\geq 1$-line graph\nof a multi-graph is the graph on the edges of the multi-graph, where two edges\nare adjacent if and only if there is at least one vertex on both edges. We\nextend Whitney's theorem to such line graphs of multi-graphs, and show that\nmost multi-graphs are uniquely determined by their line graph. Moreover, we\npresent an algorithm to determine for a given graph $\\Gamma$, if possible, a\nmulti-graph with $\\Gamma$ as line graph.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 18 May 2021 15:41:45 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-05-19"}
